// TEST: exec_self_in_plain_impl
// EXPECT: output "12"
// EXPECT: targets js, python, rust, go
//
// `Self`-in-plain-impl (codegen-completeness P3-α, item 6-go-self; folds the
// Go half of OPEN #141): a plain inherent `impl` method that names the `Self`
// type in return position (a constructor-style `combine` returning `Self`).
// Before the fix Go set `go_self_subst` only for trait-impl (value-receiver)
// methods, so an inherent-impl `Self` lowered to the placeholder `/* Self */`,
// producing uncompilable Go (`func(...) /* Self */`). The fix sets
// `go_self_subst` to the receiver type for ALL impl methods. js/python/rust
// resolve a `Self` return type in inherent impls already (Rust lowers it to its
// native `Self`).
//
// `ts` is intentionally OMITTED, mirroring `self_return.bock`: TS lowers `Self`
// to the `this` type, but the impl methods are assigned as
// `Counter.prototype.x = function(...): this { … }`, and `tsc` only permits a
// `this` type inside a class/interface member, so it rejects the assignment
// (TS2526). That is a pre-existing ts.rs codegen gap, orthogonal to this
// Go-only session and outside its ownership — surfaced as an OPEN in the PR.
// This session fixes the Go half of `self_return.bock`'s two documented gaps;
// `go` could be added to that fixture's targets as a follow-up.
//
// `main` is intentionally NOT `public`.
module main

record Counter {
  value: Int
}

impl Counter {
  fn combine(self, other: Counter) -> Self {
    return Counter { value: self.value + other.value }
  }

  fn get(self) -> Int {
    return self.value
  }
}

fn main() -> Void {
  let a: Counter = Counter { value: 5 }
  let b: Counter = Counter { value: 7 }
  let c: Counter = a.combine(b)
  println("${c.get()}")
}
